Here is a concise implementation of a queue using two stacks in Python:

```python
class Queue:
    def __init__(self):
        self.in_stack = []
        self.out_stack = []

    def enqueue(self, item):
        self.in_stack.append(item)

    def dequeue(self):
        if not self.out_stack:
            while self.in_stack:
                self.out_stack.append(self.in_stack.pop())
        return self.out_stack.pop()
```

The key ideas:

- Use one stack (in_stack) to enqueue new items 
- Use another stack (out_stack) to dequeue items
- When out_stack is empty, pop everything from in_stack and push to out_stack to reverse order

This takes O(1) time to enqueue and amortized O(1) time to dequeue.

Here is a concise program to find the common elements in two arrays without using extra data structures:

```cpp
// a and b are the input arrays
// n and m are the sizes of a and b
void printCommon(int a[], int n, int b[], int m) {
  for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
    for (int j = 0; j < m; j++) {
      if (a[i] == b[j]) {
        cout << a[i] << " ";
        break;
      } 
    }
  }
}
```

The key points are:

- Nested loops to iterate through both arrays
- Check if current element in a matches any element in b. 
- If match found, print the element and break to avoid duplicates
- No extra arrays or data structures used

